01:01:00.639 --> 01:01:06.479
But the other question was from Jeff. Great question. In your opinion,

01:01:06.479 --> 01:01:09.840
is the sports analytics community stronger in R or Python?

01:01:10.800 --> 01:01:18.479
So, the open source community is a lot stronger in R, in part because of the excellent examples set

01:01:18.479 --> 01:01:30.560
by people like Tan Ho, and Sebastian Karl of the NFLverse, Ben Baldwin, and Tej Seth, people

01:01:30.560 --> 01:01:36.320
who are making all these tutorials using NFLverse data, and as a result, there's an incredible

01:01:36.800 --> 01:01:44.080
level of knowledge of R within the open source community. And especially, it's very public on

01:01:44.080 --> 01:01:53.120
Twitter. And so, that might be part of what's influencing my opinion on this. But the industry

01:01:53.679 --> 01:02:01.040
is very much into Python, because more often than not, it's already existing within their pipelines,

01:02:01.679 --> 01:02:12.239
and more people that build applications are more familiar with Python rather than R,

01:02:12.879 --> 01:02:20.399
just because they're usually not building shiny applications for internal websites

01:02:21.520 --> 01:02:30.159
where they're displaying analytics. And so, that usually necessitates a lot of

01:02:30.320 --> 01:02:39.600
necessitates or gives somewhat of a preference to Python, because they already know how to build the

01:02:40.159 --> 01:02:45.919
APIs using those functions in Python. But there's no reason you can't use it,

01:02:46.800 --> 01:02:55.360
definitely at the team level, or even at the stats company level for Python, as long as it's not

01:02:55.360 --> 01:03:08.639
being leveraged more than several hundred times a second. And so, it's very helpful to know both,

01:03:08.639 --> 01:03:14.879
actually. I can't say enough about part of the reason I was a valuable candidate was because I

01:03:14.879 --> 01:03:24.399
knew both. And being flexible is a very useful trait as your team gets smaller.

01:03:26.479 --> 01:03:34.080
Knowing a little bit of everything is very valuable. But if you have a CS background,

01:03:35.280 --> 01:03:43.919
I would say you probably need a lot less R. But if you're coming from any background that isn't just

01:03:43.919 --> 01:03:49.280
purely CS, I would suggest learning R first, because it's a little bit easier.

01:03:50.479 --> 01:03:54.399
The learning curve is not that strong, and there's tons of examples out there. That's the other thing,

01:03:54.399 --> 01:04:02.639
is you have just loads of open code from useful developers around here who just are very generous

01:04:02.639 --> 01:04:10.639
with their time and efforts, and will show you. The community of R, our community is excellent.

01:04:10.639 --> 01:04:15.040
The people are the most helpful I've ever seen, and you can get to know them very quickly.

01:04:16.399 --> 01:04:22.320
It's not that big of a group. And so, you learn who can actually help me with this problem,

01:04:22.879 --> 01:04:29.199
and you latch on to those people, and it's like, hey, you are my friend now. This is how it works.

01:04:31.840 --> 01:04:37.120
I love that. Well, I have one more question I want to make sure we get to as well.

01:04:38.080 --> 01:04:43.760
And I see this was asked over on Slido. Keith asked, regarding players or teams following

01:04:43.760 --> 01:04:49.840
metrics, what is the percentage split of data consumed during the game versus outside the game?

01:04:53.040 --> 01:04:58.639
I'm not going to answer that as a percentage, but by far, there's much more done

01:04:59.600 --> 01:05:09.840
after the game, or outside of the game, because you only have the bandwidth to focus on so many

01:05:09.840 --> 01:05:16.560
things during the game, especially if you're trying to communicate it to the coaching staff.

01:05:17.679 --> 01:05:24.879
So, that makes limiting the amount of noise you may take during a game to only the most useful

01:05:24.879 --> 01:05:32.879
things that they can immediately make a decision on or are expecting a response on. Like, hey,

01:05:33.520 --> 01:05:40.719
should we foul here? Yes or no? And what's our best strategy in this time frame margin?

01:05:42.320 --> 01:05:49.840
That sort of stuff. But it's not like they're looking at an individual's plus minus during the

01:05:49.840 --> 01:05:57.040
game. It's like, oh, yeah, we need to get him out of here. He's a minus seven. No, that's not a thing.

